EX1:¶

In this exercise I wanted to test the three cases of the master theorem. I did that by creating three differnet functions, apply a sorting alogrithm on them, calculate the runtime and compare the f(n) with log_b(a).

The three cases are:

  1. The first case is when f(n) grows polynomially slower than log_b(a).
  2. The second case is when f(n) grows at similar rates with log_b(a).
  3. The third case is when f(n) grows polynomially faster than log_b(a).

Now, let's check the functions that I have worked on.

In the first case:¶

In the first case I used the function: T(n) = 1*T(n/2) + n where a = 1 and b = 2 and log_b(a) is log2(1)

I have created the sorting algorithm and my input was an (n) random sample and for the log_b(a) it had a corresponding sample too. I applied the sorting algorithm on both of them and It actually turned out that f(n) this had the following sum of the runtime (0.04732516399985798) which rows much much slower than log_b(a) and this had the following sum of the runtime (0.04028375699977005) which made me choose the first case for this function.

In the second case:¶

In the second case I used the function: T(n) = 1*T(n/2) + n^2 where a = 1 and b = 2 and log_b(a) is log2(1)

I have created the input which was the squared root of the first random input then I also created the corresponding input for the log_b(a) input. then I applied the function on both of them then I calculated the runtime of both of them and compared and it turned out that actually both of the sum of their input is extremly similar. The runtime sum of the f(n) is (0.054434236999441055) and the runtime sum of the log_b(a) is (0.053413957000088885) which means that both of them at similar rates so that's why we choose the second case for this function.

In the third case:¶

In the third case I used the function: T(n) = 1*T(n/2)+n^3 where a = 1 and b = 2 and log_b(a) is log2(1)

I have created the input which was the random input **3 then I also created the corresponding input for the log_b(a) input. then I applied the sorting algorithm on both of them and calculated the runtime sum. It turned out that the runtime sum of f(n) is actually much faster (0.0008489269930578303) than the runtime sum of the log_b(a) (0.0018874850065913051) which means that this is this cases represents the third case.

I will start this exercise by a question and an answer to that question. Can the Master theorem be applied on this function (T(n) = T(n/2) + n(sin(n - pi/2) + 2))? I would argue yes because we can use the n(sin(n - pi/2) + 2)) as an input to the function. This can be the itertive. In the sorting we will draw a tree and each time we will divide the input (n(sin(n - pi/2) + 2))) by the number of (a) so yes it's possible.

during the implementation of this function I chosed an upper and a lower bound for it. I divided the input by n as a lower bound and multiplyed it with an n as an upper bound.

and it actually turned out that it is boundable between these two bounds.

EX4,5:¶

In this exercise I wanted to make my algorithm faster or as fast as the built-in sorting algorithm. so first I tested my algorithm and the built-in algorithm on a 100 random integers and I found that my algorithm was faster which didn't make any sense since I just tried it on the 8,32,64 bit integers and the built-in function was way faster than mine.

so I changed the input into a 1000 random integers and the true difference actually appeared. My algorithm was way was slower than the built in function. so I wanted to make it a bit faster by trying the following approachs:

  1. I manipulated the input to make it faster than the built-in funciton. My function actually works faster on smaller inputs(hundreds) but if the input range increased then the problems starts to show up.
  2. Since my function didn't had any constants so I couldn't implement this approach
  3. I tried a third approach which is transform this function into an in place function. This made the function much faster and the runtime of it was actually really close to the built-in function runtime. the performance was stable for both small and large input data.
